sting can enhance flavor. Many varieties of roast ___ appear in cuisines around the world.","wiki"),("quail","5","Both Old World and New World ___ include edible species. The common ___ used to be much favoured in French cooking, but ___ for the table are now more likely to be domesticated Japanese ___. The common ___ is also part of Polish cuisine, Maltese cuisine, Portuguese cuisine, Italian cuisine and Indian cuisine. ___s are commonly eaten complete with the bones, since these are easily chewed and the small size of the bird makes it inconvenient to remove them.","wiki"),("horse","5","___ meat forms a significant part of the culinary traditions of many countries, particularly in Europe, South America and Asia. The top eight countries consume about 4.7 million ___s a year. For the majority of humanity's early existence, wild ___s were hunted as a source of protein.","wiki"),("llama","5","The ___  is a domesticated South American camelid, widely used as a meat and pack animal by Andean cultures since the Pre-Columbian era.","wiki"),("perch","5","___ is a common name for fish of the genus Perca, freshwater gamefish belonging to the family Percidae.  The ___, of which  three species occur in different geographical areas, lend their name to a large order of vertebrates: the Perciformes, from the Greek: πέρκη , simply meaning ___, and the Latin forma meaning shape.  Many species of freshwater gamefish more or less resemble ___, but belong to different genera. In fact, the exclusively saltwater-dwelling red drum is often referred to as a red ___, though by definition ___ are freshwater fish. Though many fish are referred to as ___ as a common name, to be considered a true ___, the fish must be of the family Percidae.","wiki"),("shark","5","___ meat is a seafood consisting of the flesh of ___s. Its consumption by humans has been mentioned since the fourth century AD in literature.","wiki"),("trout","5","___ is  the common name for a number of species of freshwater fish 